\begin_layout Subsection
Using the Raw Number of Inventors instead of Fixed-Effects
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app: Using-N-inv"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This Appendix reports the results for the main analysis presented in Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:MainResults"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 using the raw number of total inventors instead of the fixed effects from
 regression 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:one-1-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which might be inconsistently estimated.
 The following Tables, to be compared with Tables 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: RegShInvNoctrl"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: RegShInvHHI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 in the main text, show that the results are qualitatively unchanged.
 Looking at the scale of the y-axis in panel (a) of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: scattersDksh-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, it is apparent that the shares of the raw number of inventors are more
 volatile, and presents larger changes.
 This is easily explained by the fact that differences in research requirements
 across patent classes, firms and years are not absorbed as in the effective
 inventor measure.
 This greater variability simply results in larger and noisier coefficients,
 which nevertheless remain positive and significant.
