\begin_layout Subsection
Using the Lerner Index instead of the HHI
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app:Using-the-Lerner"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following Grullon et al.
 (2019), I build the Lerner Index from NBER-CES data for the period 1997-2012
 as the ratio:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Lerner}_{jt}=\frac{\text{vship}_{jt}-\text{pay}_{jt}-\text{matcost}_{jt}-\text{energy}_{jt}}{\text{vship}_{jt}},\label{eq: Lerner}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

vship
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the total value of shipments, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pay
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 denotes total payrolls, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

matcost
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

energy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 material and energy costs, respectively, and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 denotes a 6- or 4-digit NAICS sector.
 I build two alternative measures, one using 6-digit NAICS sectors, the
 original identifier in NBER-CES, and then averaging by sales at the level
 of 4-digit NAICS, or first aggregating the revenue and cost statistics
 at the level of 4-digit NAICS.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: LernerVHHI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, shows that the Lerner Index thus constructed is strongly correlated with
 the HHI measure used in the main analysis.
 However, the correlation is far from perfect, as suggested by the 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

, suggesting that this estimate of the Lerner Index might be excessively
 imprecise.
 Indeed, Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: MainWLerner"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows that, when using this measure instead of the HHI in the main analysis,
 the coefficients for the regression of inventors' shares on changes in
 concentration stay positive, but become smaller and noisier.
 This suggests the potential presence of attenuation bias, a valid concern
 due to the fact that the above measure, not based on any structural estimation,
 can only imperfectly capture markups.
 Note that this is also due to the fact that the Lerner Index is available
 only for the manufacturing sectors, which make up about 60% of the sample,
 so its use lead to dropping a substantial amount of observations.
 When using fitted values from the regression in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: LernerVHHI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to extend the measure to more sectors, as well as reducing the volatility
 of the series for available sectors, the coefficients recover magnitudes
 and significance close to the baseline presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: RegShInvHHI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

